ia_key": "13_2050942548001337344"}}, "media_url_https": "https://pbs.twimg.com/amplify_video_thumb/2050942548001337344/img/WaIq8LzTNKvyZWj1.jpg", "original_info": {"focus_rects": [], "height": 720, "width": 1280}, "sizes": {"large": {"h": 720, "w": 1280}}, "type": "video", "url": "https://t.co/KibEpuiSMT", "video_info": {"aspect_ratio": [16, 9], "duration_millis": 14966, "variants": [{"content_type": "application/x-mpegURL", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2050942548001337344/pl/Or_tQGCRzSHgQTJK.m3u8?tag=27"}, {"bitrate": 256000, "content_type": "video/mp4", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2050942548001337344/vid/avc1/480x270/GuQCb8x0EJ3QAhU0.mp4?tag=27"}, {"bitrate": 832000, "content_type": "video/mp4", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2050942548001337344/vid/avc1/640x360/Kee8rYaISwdWJego.mp4?tag=27"}, {"bitrate": 2176000, "content_type": "video/mp4", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2050942548001337344/vid/avc1/1280x720/tLkVwiYw6kPm9D7Y.mp4?tag=27"}]}}]}, "card": null, "place": {}, "entities": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "timestamps": [], "urls": [{"display_url": "youtu.be/QoDLCVEFu3Y?si\u2026", "expanded_url": "https://youtu.be/QoDLCVEFu3Y?si=s2F5BiUKMv1frW61", "indices": [90, 113], "url": "https://t.co/vt30njGOSW"}], "user_mentions": []}, "quoted_tweet": null, "retweeted_tweet": null, "isLimitedReply": false, "communityInfo": null, "article": null}, {"type": "tweet", "id": "2050924148772511943", "url": "https://x.com/aakashgupta/status/2050924148772511943", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/aakashgupta/status/2050924148772511943", "text": "Alex Conley is paralyzed from the neck down. He just flew that P-51 Mustang with his thoughts.\n\nConley is patient two in Neuralink's PRIME study. A car rollover in 2021 severed his cervical spinal cord. In July 2024 a surgical robot threaded 64 polyimide ribbons (each thinner than a tenth of a human hair) into the hand-and-arm strip of his motor cortex, distributing 1,024 electrodes across the patch of brain that used to send signals to the muscles he can no longer move.\n\nHis motor cortex never stopped firing. When Conley imagines flexing his fingers, the same neurons fire that fired before the wreck, into a nerve highway disconnected since 2021. The implant listens. Spike detection isolates individual neurons. A decoder maps the population pattern to whatever output you wire it to.\n\nA cursor. CAD software. Counter-Strike 2. A robotic arm. An RC plane.\n\nBefore the accident, Conley was an automotive technician. He used the Neuralink to write the Arduino code that translates his motor cortex output into a four-axis \"quad stick\" controller protocol, then routes that to the plane's transmitter. He typed the code with his thoughts. He compiled it with his thoughts. He flies the plane with his thoughts. The chip programmed its own next interface.\n\nThe whole pipeline runs at about 10 bits per second. A 1971 acoustic modem had higher throughput. That's enough to fly a P-51 because the brain compresses intent before it leaves the cortex. You don't think about every muscle fiber. You think \"left wing down.\" The decoder reads \"left wing down.\" The aileron deflects.\n\nAbout 20 of these patients exist now. Patient 18 is a British paratrooper named Jon Noble, raiding World of Warcraft hands-free from London. Patient 1, Noland, paralyzed since a 2016 diving accident, browses the web and plays Mario Kart. They're all routing the same anatomical region into completely different downstream devices.\n\nThe spinal cord was a single-output wire. The cortex isn't.\n\nHis motor cortex never knew the limb was gone.", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 4, "replyCount": 3, "likeCount": 18, "quoteCount": 0, "viewCount": 3350, "createdAt": "Sun May 03 13:03:16 +0000 2026", "lang": "en", "bookmarkCount": 8, "isReply": false, "inReplyToId": null, "conversationId": "2050924148772511943", "displayTextRange": [0, 276], "inReplyToUse